english:
  title: A Petition of Gratitude to His Majesty Upon Passing the Examination
  author: Lin Zongbi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When swift horses race ahead, the ant mounds tremble with concern. Yet the Luo hen, by its warmth, hatches the swan's egg to soar beyond the clouds. Such grace weighs heavier than mountains, stirring emotions as turbulent as ice and fire.

    I have long pondered: talent emerges for the world's sake, yet virtuous men appear in every age. Nations flourish through worthy ministers, and rulers thirst for capable servants. Yet people harbor ambitions like jade dragons drawing frogs in their wake—wise and foolish alike compete and clash. Things often wear false appearances; many wear sheep's skin over tiger's hide, so truth and falsehood mingle indistinguishably. Knowing men is no easy matter. Even the sages found it troublesome. Without careful selection, how could worthy talent be discovered?

    When King Wen sought scholars, though Zhou was ancient, its mandate became new. When Emperor Wu elevated the virtuous, Han gained men and flourished thereby. In Jin, they tested sutras and characters. In Tang, they opened the Broad Rhetoric and Select Excellence examinations. All aimed to find capable talent, raising standards high. To pass such examinations—is this not worthy of honor?

    Yet the scholar Ping Zun's ascent required ten submissions before his hair whitened. Han Yu, like a soaring dragon, achieved one position only to see his youth fade. Lu Dalang possessed heroic talent but remained clothed in hemp all his days. Qian Sigong commanded literary grace yet never saw his name inscribed on the yellow scroll. The examination halls have proven arduous since ancient times—rocky paths and difficult terrain through which even the worthy struggle to advance.

    Alas, when the age decayed, these examinations fell to ruin. Some selected by household rank rather than virtue. Some hired by the cartload, losing true talent. They mistook the deer for jade—ignorant men like Li Linfu filled the ranks. They spat out phoenixes in verse—but who recognized the divine understanding of Yang Xiong? The worthy and unworthy shared the same stable, indistinguishable. Among the gentry, some strike their chests and sigh toward heaven. Long accustomed to corruption, the malady deepens. For centuries the literary tradition withered. Yet in these thousand years after, our great sage-emperor appeared, shining with grace, spreading education's transformation.

    The transformative influence flows boundlessly. The scripts of Xia and Shang spread through the world. The songs of Qi and Lu rise in noble harmony. The ruler's wisdom brings common blessing. Scholars all desire to serve at court.

    Yet I—cast aside and reversed—am one of the foolish and ridiculous. My understanding reaches not the nine-ribbed tortoise of the deep river. My knowledge grasps not the six-headed beast of the crimson elder. I wandered north to the white waters, scarcely approaching madness's forgetting. I gazed south seeking lost pearls, befuddled as one blind from birth. Afflicted by malady, I strayed from the path of righteousness.

    Those who inherit sealed kinships—like Kim Il-je with his seven generations of office—I cannot emulate. Those who display fearless strength—like Xu Chu with tiger's brawn—I lack. Without learning, I cannot navigate the world. Without grasping ancient and modern forms, how differ I from oxen in garments? Ignorant of heaven and earth's wholeness, how shall I glimpse the gnat's hidden flight?

    So I took my books and traveled far to seek a teacher. I crossed great waters, seeking wisdom's source. I sang in admiration of the banished immortal, danced in morning streams, and bathed in sacred waters. I returned to the sage's gate. I studied the blue-boxed commentaries. I discussed Yang Xiong's subtle phrases. Late in coming to the Tao, though I grasped its dregs, how could one who merely visits the sage's threshold truly speak?

    Yet suddenly, in my youthful folly, I craved swift advancement. My meager talent wished to pierce willow leaves at a hundred paces. My heart hoped to pluck a single branch of laurel. I sought to repay my parents' care, believing this my path to fulfillment. I raised my head, awaiting selection by examination, each day stretching like a year.

    But—alas!—like a boat requiring no waves, like a tree seeking stillness while winds persist—calamity struck suddenly. I could not fulfill the final rites. With five siblings, I mourned at the Luo's bend. With a solitary mother, I wandered like an exile in Lu. With finite life, I encountered unmeasured suffering. Unable to speak or appeal, my spirit could not soar. Thus did I languish, resembling the exile Qu Yuan in his grief.

    I saw my form wasted, my countenance gaunt. Carters and innkeepers scorned me alike. Though my ambitions burned with shame at drowning, none knew it. Fearing this might be my end, I turned to others' labor. I became a servant carrying rice, then joined a nobleman's retinue. Long did I labor before the horse, my back scarred from the whip. I ate beans and bore endless shame. Often did I taste the bitterness of rejection—even spittle upon my face.

    Dust followed my footsteps. Thorns emerged from my scholarly mouth. Many times my mother's threads, carefully sewn, barely held my garments together. Though I possessed fields like Su Qin spoke of, I could scarce afford gruel. This soil brought only harm, my labor yielding no sustenance. Though I dwelt in poverty, I remained ragged, hungry and cold.

    Yet still I read in stolen moments, and my teachers marveled. My brothers laughed in mockery. How could one so lowly pursue rank? Why torture yourself with learning, they said, when letters merely record names? They urged me to abandon study, dismissing it all as futile. Like dogs in different lands, all their voices barked the same dismissal.

    Following Xun Li's example, I seemed not to hear. Like Sun Jing, I learned what I had not yet learned, resolved not to cease until death. I strove that my skill might match Wen's eight transformations, my name extend Yang's threefold goodness. Yet sparrows mock the great roc's flight—how could ants comprehend the swan's aspiration?

    My talent was shallow, my ambitions wide. Unable to build lasting skill, I became inept. I heaped up sand trying to solidify it into the eagle's wing. I dangled the great fisherman's twelve oxen—yet never caught a glimpse of fish. Long did I soil this scholar's robe, finding no room in the world's path. I gazed upon Zhang Zhe's ten thousand selections—only sighing with Liang Hong's five laments.

    How could this be remedied? My straits seemed insurmountable. I knew well the ancients' tales: Sima Xiangru's verse soared cloudlike yet his home held four bare walls. Fan Sheng's library overflowed his belly, yet coins never filled his purse. Huo Guang required no learning to command ten thousand households. Tian Qianqiu spoke one phrase and became chancellor. Some gained rank through chess, others through grapes—talent and circumstance matter less than meeting one's time.

    Surely I need not exhaust myself through study? Should fortune appear possible, I'd even grasp a whip as servant. Should burden grow heavy, I'd rest anywhere. Let the hunted deer flee to treacherous paths—why seek Eastern Peak's depths? Let the stranded fish expire—why await the Western River's opening? Better abandon this bumbling scholar's art, relying on ancestral merit for advance. Better seek position among court luminaries, taking the official path early. Cast aside these tattered books—why seek dusty pages? Embrace fine silks and savor present pleasures!

    Yet truly, when I reflected upon this path—when those seeking virtue do not abandon it midway, when one dons the scholar's robe, other arts cannot touch it—especially remembering my late father's parting words, spoken as he held my hand:

    "I possessed no surpassing talent, merely serving as one attendant near the throne. I gazed upon heaven's blue and beheld day's white light. Within arm's reach, I honored the court's dignity. With dark hair not yet silvered, I joined the ranks of officials. For me, this sufficed. What more could I seek? Yet having not studied the ancients before taking office, this grieves and pains me. Just as the speckled ox's calf, if its coat glows ruddy and horns grow straight, may be sacrificed to the gods, so too may the gnarled tree root, if shown proper care, become a worthy vessel. You must endeavor! Study and practice with care. Never pursue the common and vulgar. Let your brilliance shine through letters."

    His words still echo in my ears as vividly as yesterday! How could I live basely, indistinguishable from the degenerate age? If I merely grasped the petty clerk's knife and brush, how could I ascend my ancestor's tomb? Thus I grip my books and forget fatigue. With careful resolve, I tend my conduct.

    Unless I penetrate the iron inkstone of Sang Weihan, unless I swear to no other path, I shall sit on the humble woven mat of Guan Ning, illuminating the sage's learning, bending toward it as years pass. I sought to glimpse clarity in dimness. I heard propriety from Yuan Banqian, received literary arts from Guo Zhengyi. I grasped the thread of the Tao, wished to observe the realm's light. Though useless to the time, unconcerned with meanness, when I observed the approaching hour, I advanced to the examination for selecting talented scholars.

    Suddenly my hidden potential emerged—like a pick thrust through a sack. I rose to rank above others. Though I lacked Dong Zhongshu's vast undertaking, I preceded elder scholars, surprising all with youth's achievement. I brought small comfort to my mother waiting at the door, opening a humble path forward. Then I first understood how precious it is to be a scholar.

    Since then I have devoted myself here, further inspiring my negligent spirit. I shall not follow those who abandon their course midway. I shall sweep bamboo from the Weihe valley to bind into books. I shall gather pines from the Zuolai mountains to supply my writing tools. I seek to deepen my study and grasp the Tao, to broadly record and complete my learning.

    From the dragon diagrams of Fuxi, the mirrors of the Yellow Emperor—their deep sources—through the proclamations of Zhou, the inscribed vessels of Shang with their twisted phrases, even to strategies of field battle and city siege, to the discourse of poets and ink-followers: though I have not penetrated all, I shall survey them broadly.

    When flowers bloom and moonlight shines, I guard against the poison of ease. In the burial ground of brushes and forest of words, I recognize the life and death of page-devouring insects. Though I gather learning and inquire carefully, these are but childhood habits grown white with age. I remain dark to the subtle meanings of obsessive transmission, knowing only the minor arts of book cases. I clutch at yanshi stones, mistaking them for treasures, hoarding them deeply. Observing autumn waters filling the banks, I boast of abundance. Confusedly bewildered, multiplying delusions—purely constant, seemingly mad—I merely adorn my plumage.

    Like the white shrike of Tongguan, I sharpen talons and beak, vainly imitating the yellow hawk of Lu. My writing, though inferior to Xie's gold fragments, falsely claims Chen's startled assembly. I once thought none surpassed me. Now who could match such presumption? Should I await imperial summons at Gold Horse Gate, I'd not yield to Dongfang Mianqian's memorials. Should I compare arts at White Tiger Hall, I'd scarcely approach Ding Zi's discourse.

    With this I'd ascend—cloudlike heights within days. With such persuasion of my lord, gold and jade would materialize mid-conversation! Yet I never measured my utterly insufficient talents, merely blathering through conduct's examination. When the sage's summons suddenly descended, that thousand-buddha scripture alone filled my mind. My solitary self could scarce encounter the nine-fold palace's recognition.

    The flying yellow steed soars without heeding toads; the howling monsters bring contempt from otters. My feet find no purchase. Who would pity me? When times arrive, I shall act—needing no envy of such kinds. How dare I feast on pheasant delicacies, forever dwelling like serpent broth? The Canglan's waters can wash my hat-cord. When comes my auspicious hour? The bright pearl's light compels the sword-bearer. Self-advancement proves genuinely difficult.

    Feasting on smartweed and drinking ice, I admire the Yue king's gall-tasting. Pillow upon spear, awaiting dawn, I fear Zu Sheng will wield the whip before me—like the dragon coiled in mud whose rising depends on itself, like the cock's cry in wind and rain that ceases not for dark or dawn.

    Treasure upon the mat—yes, I shall wait its price. When the sun stands highest, observe the swift. The moment arrives, the moment arrives—why comes it late? Ever awaiting Mo Di and Ke Qing to bring news of the gilt-clay joyful letter. The Kuai ice-seller hastened, yet ice melts rapidly. Kuafu chased the sun unresting, yet the sun recedes ever distant. Unknown causes bring silent arrival before one. Though wisdom flourishes, it cannot equal riding fortune's tide.

    Among scholars remains scholar-conduct; among Daoists remains Daoist-conduct. I merely cultivate the path I walk. Only sages recognize sages; only worthy men know worthy men. I sought none who would hear and respond. In scrolls I constantly encounter sages, inwardly practicing the unnamed, blending light with dust—whether similar or dissimilar matters not. I sharpen fists and quicken feet. Whether action or possible action, all belong to the realm of possibility.

    Confronting the exceptional, I again summoned my depleted breath. Though skill trails behind Ding's butcher-blade—unable to grasp the nineteen-year-old bull-knife—I seek courage like Meng Shesha's, determined to match a thousand thousand enemies. Following wind through select talent, I bow at the high altar. My robe shines silver-bright—all bearing Yuan-era genius. My writings flow like connected brocade—wholly elevated, transcendent words. The confused scholar-masses bearing books, their towering heroic ambitions each guard firm walls, all desiring death in place.

    Brush-battle raises wind; standards shield the sky. Sunlight grows thin as they cough forth thunderbolt prose. Magic pearls respond to hand, racing forth. We gaze upon city-base covenants, countable as fingers in a boat. My single mediocre nature entered the throng of keen-edged rivals. Though seeking fervent ardor, we mutually encroached. Bai Zhi's mouth still drips milk—how dare he match Han Xin's prowess? Zhou Song's throat runs dry—he merely begs Yuan Gong for drink.

    My heart flutters like a flag; my belly burns, parched. The high ones enter heaven—is it only the subtle mystery of the Great Mystery? Silent, I abandon the brush—nearly bringing the worry of trailing white. Though fortune blessed my words, in truth I swerve without law. Drawing snakes, adding feet—not merely Xun Zi's small flaw but Pei Gong's numerous blemishes unavoided.

    I expected to mark my brow, desperately grasping at wind—how could I expect Wang Wei's five shortcomings to rank among Pang Yan's three-tiered foremost? Walking high through Dragon Gate waves, though obtaining the bright pearl proves difficult, I contentedly claim the chicken's mouth position, rejoicing that I avoid the ox's rear.

    Inevitably ranked among five-hundred-year-appearing worthies, towering as sixteenth-ranked generals' strange descendant. One call startles—though I cannot flap the heaven-piercing wing, second arrows strike all killed, achieving center-bull success. I myself marvel at the horse-losing elder's fate, becoming the linked-bird guest.

    Morning finds me blocked in narrow lanes; evening opens upon broad streets. Light silks warm me; elegant garments lighten. Fragrance moistens the apricot garden's crimson snow. Jade whip binds four horses, advancing through ghost-realm clouds. Joy fills each stride, all transformed into single-moment delight. My name, Zizhen, greatly shines. Luo Yin's regret dissolves entirely.

    Several years like dragon-serpents in Feng city, emptily harboring purple vapors. One dawn like Liu An's chickens and dogs ascending blue heaven. Quietly contemplating unranked glory, surely some shadowed assistance exists. This derives from a certain official whose path enters the deepest waters where great creatures swim, whose learning rivals the unicorn's horn in singularity.

    Inwardly cultivated, he possesses utmost stalwart vitality responding to ten thousand functions. Outwardly manifest, he displays celestial brilliance ordering hundred officials. He Xiao's rigorous character stands like a thousand-foot straight pine. Shu Du's broad vessel extends like ten-thousand-acre waters.

    His words gain mountain-river's aid. His fearsome reputation even children know. He is the Jiangzuo's supreme talent, Han-south's sole exemplar. Sailing to the upper kingdom, northern scholars yield precedence. Donning brocade returning homeward, eastern capital's lord sighs in wonder.

    Thus obtaining the ruler's exclusive favor, unmatched in court, when he ascends the Panhong terrace lecturing sacred classics, all understand. When he dwells in the orchid province drafting imperial edicts, clerks' wrists wear thin. His position joins clear, crucial offices—men called him "a single thread of pure ice." Returning nightly from forbidden depths' severity, the Son of Heaven sends him twin-lotus candles.

    Court ministers behold him with longing eyes. Literary scholars look up reverently. Early bearing noble fame—like the five phoenixes of Fenyin, fine judging of character—like the two dragons of Pingyu. He constantly made the common folk's unfulfilled desires his own sorrow, causing worthy persons to delight in proclaiming goodness.

    I heard his teachings! Is not the literary way here? Simplicity within the imperial heart, he presides over selection meetings opening the water-mirror's discernment. Searching laterally, he discovered jade-bamboo students. Within Lu Xiangong's selections, he specially champions the dragon-tiger register. Within Quan Sikong's household, again gleam phoenix-and-luan talents.

    Though the Terrace and Lai already gained worthy men, Guan and Kuai shall substitute for surplus. Among the mediocre and dull, such elevation occurs! Obtaining Bole's horse-knowledge, worth tripled. Meeting Xun Shuo's ox-regard, bells harmonized with nine-melody music.

    Considering my private share, I secretly rejoice and feel moved. Repaying grace like heaven's—boundless—I can only press palm to brow, words failing. I solemnly swear to avoid the slippery grease of conduct, holding ice and harsh bark in my heart, vowing to praise Zhang Gong's three-baskets glory-bringing writing, desiring not to let Cui's one estate fall fallow, taking the name "Grateful Child."

    Speech exhausts, feeling presses—how could brush and tongue suffice?
